As we make our return to school on Monday, we ask our families to ensure you are monitoring your students for any concerning symptoms before sending them to school. Students exhibiting concerning symptoms will be sent home.

Also, as a reminder, masks MUST be worn on school buses and all students who can safely do so, are highly encouraged to wear masks at school when they are unable to practice social distancing.

All staff members will be masking when they are unable to maintain social distancing.

As a final reminder, all meals will be free to students starting Monday! This program will run through December 31st or until the funding stream runs out.

post_text:
Awesome announcement!

The USDA has made the decision to fund meals for all students, meaning ALL student meals will be free temporarily.

This program is scheduled to run until December 31st, OR until the funding runs out.

Families who have not submitted a current free/reduced application will still need to do so ASAP because when the funding ends, meals will go back to being full price automatically.

Any meal charges/balances on accounts that have already been made prior to this programs implementation will still need to be paid, those fees are not forgiven.

We will send a note home next week to help ensure all families are made aware of the new program!

K-12 Activity from Ms. Hinkle: Make a Family Bucket List
Here‚Äôs how to do it:
‚Ä¢Get your family together and collect a piece of paper (or use the template provided https://childhood101.com/create-a-family-bucket-list-printable/) and some markers.
‚Ä¢As a family, brainstorm a list of accomplishments, experiences, or achievement goals that you want to work towards as a family over the next year.
‚Ä¢At the end of the year, look back over your list and see what you‚Äôve accomplished.
‚Ä¢Celebrate the goals you accomplished as a family.

Bronaugh R-VII is seeking applicants for a part time Lunch Clerk. The applicant must be self-motivated, willing to read through manuals and attend trainings in order to complete the job effectively and thoroughly. The applicant should be quick and comfortable with computers and willing to work with money, lunch charges, billing, and record keeping.

If you are interested please visit our website www.bronaughschools.net and fill out the application under employment opportunities. Applicants do not need to submit three letters of recommendation but they must provide contact information for three references from previous employers or supervisors. This reference information should be emailed to jdickey@bronaugh.k12.mo.us

Bronaugh R-VII District Update:

This afternoon after school let out, we were made aware one of our high school staff members tested positive for COVID-19. At this time, the Vernon County Health Department has begun initial contact tracing and notification of students who are considered to be close contacts. Close contact is defined as closer than 6 feet for 15 minutes or more. The district is continuing all of our extra sanitation practices and school will be open tomorrow.

As always, we urge you to speak to your child about measures to prevent the possible spread of COVID-19 such as hand washing, not touching their face, and social distancing. Please call your health care provider for questions specifically related to your child‚Äôs health.

We appreciate your continued support and patience as we navigate this incredibly challenging time. We will get through this together. Thank you and have a good evening.

Bronaugh Athletics Booster Club
August 27 at 10:38 AM ¬∑

We wanted to share the guidelines for any spectator attending the volleyball game at Pleasanton on Tuesday, Sept 1st. We will do our best to keep you updated on the procedures of the schools we will be visiting, but be prepared for all situations in advance. We appreciate you respecting the guidelines of our host schools and your patience as we navigate the changes together.

Pleasanton requirements are outlined below.

Since volleyball is in an indoor event. We ask that all spectators wear masks while in the gym, at the concession stand and bathrooms.

Contactless temperature checks will be performed for all spectators as they enter the building. Spectators with a temperature above 100 degrees will be asked to return home.

Social distancing where possible, we encourage families to sit in clusters and leave distance between families. Parents please keep small children with you to ensure their safety.

Frequent hand washing or sanitizing

We encourage you to stay home if you are not feeling well or have been in contact with someone who is not feeling well.

We desperately need more substitutes and if you are interested, we encourage you to click on this link for more information!

If you have 60 semester hours of experience, you can head straight to dese.mo.gov to apply for a sub certificate using the traditional route!

post_text: Thanks to local farmers and Bayer Fund, Bronaugh R-VII received an @AmericasFarmers Grow Rural Education grant. We are excited to use these funds to enhance STEM curriculum by providing Chromebooks for each elementary student, grades 1-6 in order to implement a new STEM program called Farm to Classroom. Farm to Classroom brings together local farmers with students through peer-mentoring, STEM learning, community outreach, and agricultural field trips. The Farm to Classroom program educates students in the processes involved in successful farming operations through the use of science, technology, engineering, and math. Bronaugh FFA students will partner with our elementary teachers to create monthly agriculture lessons that bring area farmers, and their practices, to the classroom for the purpose of engaging younger generations and empowering them to become future leaders of the agriculture industry.

shared_text:
Bronaugh Athletics Booster Club
June 6 at 1:43 PM ¬∑

Job well done! In only 10 work hours and our amazing volunteers we checked tasks off the lists. Removal of old outfield fence and posts, set 57 new posts, welded 550 feet of new top rail in place, primed 550 feet of fence, painted 57 posts Wildcat green, and set 8 new posts for the batting cage.

It was hot! Students spent time Friday am pulling old fence down, then at 6pm and a wonderful 92' degrees we started setting posts, finishing up in the dark. Welders started Saturday at 7am, volunteers showing up around 8am with a temp of 80' already, finished by noon at 92'

I can't put into words the amazing community we have. We are so thankful for each and everyone of you, you show up time after time! We will finish the project in October, when it's a little cooler and we have the rest of our materials.

P-EBT Information posted on our website:
https://www.bronaugh.k12.mo.us/?p=9793
Under the Families First Coronavirus Response Act of 2020, families that qualify for free or reduced price meals at school may be eligible for a new one-time Pandemic Electronic Benefits Transfer (P-EBT) of up to $302 per child (Pre-Kindergarten ‚Äì Grade 12) to help cover the cost of meals students have eaten at home on days that schools have been closed. Students can receive P-EBT benefits even if they have been or continue to receive meals provided by the school district during the school closure. If your child was not previously eligible for free or reduced price meals, but you have now lost income, you may be eligible to receive P-EBT benefits (review the P-EBT Eligibility Criteria document below).

Join me in Congratulating Gail Shaw on being named Bronaugh R-VII's CHAMPION OF THE YEAR!
The district's Champion award goes to someone who comes to work everyday with a fantastic attitude and a willingness to serve others! Gail keeps our school running behind the scenes and most don't fully comprehend all of the work she does to make sure our school can keep moving forward! Gail has truly made my first year as Superintendent easier as she has answered a LOT of questions and shown extreme patience. We love and appreciate this wonderful lady!
Thank you for everything you do, Mrs. Shaw!

Our Junior class and their sponsors really wanted to be able to put on a prom for this school year. We appreciate their dedication and the work they will put into making this happen.

PENDING ALLOWANCES BY THE COUNTY AND STATE OF MO:
Prom will be Saturday, July 25th at the Enchanted Prairie Farm. Walk-in at 6:30PM - Dance from 7pm to Midnight.

The Juniors will be sending out invitations to the Seniors. (Juniors and Seniors who intend to bring a date who is not a current student at Bronaugh need to email those requests to Mr. Wait for approval! All dates must be at least a freshman and UNDER 21!) Dates need to be signed up by June 26th.

post_text:
The following is pending restrictions being lifted! We will adjust if we find out we won't be able to safely hold summer weights:

Next Year's 7th-12th Graders: Weights and Conditioning May 26-July 2nd

The first week will start the Tuesday after Memorial Day. We will go Tuesday-Friday of that week (May 26-29).
The weeks following we will go Monday-Thursday.

The kids need to check their emails and "vote" on a time. The times are:
6am-8am 5pm-7pm
7am-9am
8am-10am 6pm-8pm
9am-11am

By voting, I will be able to set up a time that gets the most kids to show up and participate. If we get a good number of morning and evening votes, I will do 2 sessions (morning and evening). But I need at least 8-10 kids in each session if we are to do 2 sessions. You can vote for "multiple times" or vote "ALL" Please email me your vote ASAP!

All kids from 7th-12th grade that plan on playing "any" sports next year are welcome!!

post_text:
I'm really missing our families today and wanted to drop a note to all who have been SO KIND to us during this closure as we struggle to make some tough decisions and adapt to a new normal of schooling. Everything is new and it is challenging to not have our staff and students in our building. We're trying our hardest and I TRULY appreciate those of you who have spread your kindness into our lives during this frustrating time!

I firmly believe when we ASSUME THE BEST out of everyone instead of immediately assuming ill-intent, we can lead MUCH happier lives. Our families are the best and I can never thank you enough for making Bronaugh the BEST PLACE TO BE! Kind words get me through my day!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: ALLY TURNER!!

Parents/Guardians:
Mom: Rhonda Turner

BHS clubs/activities:
Yearbook-1yr, Art Club-1yr, Volleyball-3yrs, Cheer-3yrs, FCCLA-4yrs, Science Club-4yrs, FCA-3yrs, Student Council-2yrs, NHS-3yrs, Speech and Debate-4yrs, Upward Bound-4yrs

Future plans:
I plan to attend Pittsburg State University and major in Elementary Education with a minor in business. I plan to become a pre-k to first grade teacher but have business to fall back on.

Long term goals:
I plan to get married have no more than 3 children and own a beach house.

Favorite memory:
I can't choose just one memory, I have attended Bronaugh school since preschool. It has been like a second home to me. I will cherish every memory, and I am sad to see it come to an end so suddenly.

Ally Turner

post_text: We were just made aware of this announcement. Please know we will communicate with our families as soon as we have more information for you regarding end of year things and collecting belongings from school.
shared_text:
Governor Mike Parson
April 9 at 2:56 PM ¬∑

We are ordering all Missouri public and charter schools to remain closed through the remainder of the academic year with the exceptions of nutrition services and child care that are outlined in our recent health order.

This recommendation was made by working together with the Missouri Department of Elementary and Secondary Education and several school superintendents from across the state -- from both urban and rural districts.

Schools should continue remote learning for their students until the end date previously set on their academic calendars.

For scheduling purposes:
We have a tentative backup date for Graduation for JUNE 20th! Mark your calendars! This date will only be used if we can not have our regularly scheduled graduation in May. Graduation would remain at 7pm. Information about Baccalaureate would come later if we have to postpone.

We wanted to give our families as much notice as possible about the date so you can get it on your calendars. We're still optimistic we could graduate in May as planned but want to be proactive with planning.

If they haven't already, your child's teachers will be reaching out soon to ask a few questions regarding what type of internet access or devices you have at home. We've had several requests for things for our kiddos to work on while at home so our teachers are working to come up with activities and enrichment opportunities for our students while we are on this extended Wellness Break.

We fully understand not all of our families have access to internet or devices so the survey helps us see how we can best reach everyone. Nothing the school will be sending out is mandatory or for a grade; it is all enrichment based so parents have some great resources to use with their students while we are away.

If you have any questions please call the office and talk to Mr. Wait! 417-922-3211

Some exciting news for your Saturday! While we are sad to see Mrs. Kailey and her husband move to KC for Mr. Jungmann‚Äôs new job, We are pleased to announce the hire of Whitney Hinkle as Guidance Counselor / At-Risk Coordinator beginning the 20-21 School Year!

‚ÄúAfter nine years of teaching 3rd grade, I‚Äôm very excited to take on a new role as the Guidance Counselor/At Risk Coordinator. Although I‚Äôm not a new face, here‚Äôs a little info about me. I graduated from Bronaugh R-VII in 2006 (life-long Wildcat) & then from Missouri Southern State University in 2010 (Bachelor of Science in Education). Currently at our school, I‚Äôm the director of our after school program, serve on various committees & coordinate our quarterly Wildcat Day, along with teaching 3rd grade. When I‚Äôm not at school, I enjoy spending time with my family & friends, especially my adorable niece & nephew! I feel very blessed to have this opportunity to serve our school in a new way. I look forward to building new relationships & continuing to guide our school to be all that it can be! üíö‚Äù

post_text:
As we continue to follow guidance from our local authorities and in cooperation with our neighboring school districts, we are making the difficult decision to close our schools through April 3rd. This is uncharted territory for everyone and the situation continues to change by the minute. We will continue to keep you updated as we go along.

Beginning Monday, March 23rd, we will begin serving FREE meals to all children 18 & under in the community. Meals will be served grab & go at the Bronaugh High School and Moundville Community Center at 8:30AM each morning, Monday through Friday. Please stay in your vehicle, we will bring them out to you. We will serve breakfast and lunch at the same time for you to take to your homes. If you are in the situation of needing meals delivered to your home, PLEASE let us know and we are happy to make arrangements to meet your needs. For meal preparation purposes, please go to this link: http://bit.ly/WildcatMeals

Last Friday 3 Freshman girls represented Bronaugh at our District speech Tournament. The young ladies all did an amazing Job. There were 22 Schools attending. The following students placed in their events:
Trinity Haynes- 4th in Humourous Interpretation
Mazie Bogart- 7th in Dramatic Interpretation
Mazie and Trinity- 7th in Duet Acting
Chloe Hoye- competed in both Poetry and Radio

All of the girls worked hard and did a fantastic job representing Bronaugh. They went up against schools like Joplin and Neosho.
